I happen to own a bunch of Google-TV devices including the Sony Blu-Ray, NSZ-GS7, ASUS Cube, and Visio Co Star.  There are differences in playback depending on device.  For example, MKV video plays fine on the Sony or ASUS Cube but there is no audio on the Visio Co Star.   As well, high bit-rate video segments (like 1080p action sequences) can have decoding issues on the weaker processor models.  So, for example, I will have an issue with the Google-TV Gen 1 Sony Blu Ray but not the Google-TV Gen 2 Sony NSZ-GS7.   These may be more device related dependencies than software related.

I have an ASUS O!Play, and it will keep playing whatever directory you start a video from, until it reaches the end of the directory, or you hit stop.  Those two minor details aside, this is a great G.TV app!  But I sure would love to see those two details get resolved ^_^
replyContent: To play all files in a directory, long click the first file, you'll see a context menu with "Play this and next files" option.

Other than NetFlix...  I have a wide variety of video files stored locally on my LAN.  Most of these are ripped DVDs, some are DRM stripped files from iTunes, while others are FLVs downloaded from various websites.  GTVBox plays all these files perfectly, straight off the media share of my NAS.  The interface is simple, not flashy.  And it's FAST.  Previously, I watched most of this content via a SageTV HD200 box, which took forever moving through the directory structure of my NAS, especially once I got several directories deep. This app is lightning fast, allowing me to drill down to the show I want to watch in just a few seconds, no matter how deep in the structure.  I've tried the AirPlay feature out (without DRM'ed files) and it worked fine.
